TY  - JOUR
T1  - Strength in Numbers? Gender Composition, Leadership, and Women’s Influence in Teams
AU  - Karpowitz, Christopher F.
AU  - O’Connell, Stephen D.
AU  - Preece, Jessica
AU  - Stoddard, Olga
Y1  - 2024/01/23
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/729578
DO  - 10.1086/729578
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3077
EP  - 3114
VL  - 132
IS  - 9
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This article studies the effect of team gender composition and leadership on women?s influence in two field experiments. Study 1 finds that male-majority teams accord disproportionately less influence to women and are less likely to choose women to represent the team externally. We replicate this finding in a new context, where we also vary the gender of an assigned team leader. We find that a female leader substantially increases women?s influence, even in male-majority teams. With a model of discriminatory voting, we show that either increasing women's share or assigning a female leader decreases the penalty women face by more than 50%.
AB  - This article studies the effect of team gender composition and leadership on women?s influence in two field experiments. Study 1 finds that male-majority teams accord disproportionately less influence to women and are less likely to choose women to represent the team externally. We replicate this finding in a new context, where we also vary the gender of an assigned team leader. We find that a female leader substantially increases women?s influence, even in male-majority teams. With a model of discriminatory voting, we show that either increasing women's share or assigning a female leader decreases the penalty women face by more than 50%.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/729578
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/729578
Y2  - 2024/10/27
